# Governance

How this project's AI setup — the charter — is owned, changed, and maintained.
The charter is everything an agent reads to work here: `CLAUDE.md`, `.claude/`
(rules, skills, commands, agents, features, plans, evals), `GLOSSARY.md`, and
this file. Application code is governed by the rules; this file governs the
rules themselves.

## Ownership

| Area | Owner | Notes |
|------|-------|-------|
| `CLAUDE.md` (constitution) | [role/person] | Changes need [review level]. |
| `.claude/rules/` | [role/person] | Rule authors; see layer litmus in `rules/README.md`. |
| `.claude/skills/`, `commands/`, `agents/` | [role/person] | |
| `.claude/features/`, `GLOSSARY.md` | [anyone / role] | Low-ceremony; keep current. |
| This file | [role/person] | |

## Layers & authority

Rules carry a `layer`: `project` | `team` | `personal` (see `.claude/rules/README.md`).

- **`locked: true`** rules are iron laws. Overriding one is a **deviation** — it
  must be surfaced and justified, never silent.
- An inner layer may not silently contradict an outer layer. [Name who resolves conflicts.]

## Changing the charter

1. Open a change against the relevant file(s). One concern per change.
2. Every new/changed rule states its **`why`** — the incident or principle it prevents.
3. [Review requirement — e.g. "one owner approval; iron-law changes need two."]
4. Log material changes in `CHARTER-CHANGELOG.md` (or this repo's changelog).
5. Regenerate `.claude/INDEX.json` if artifacts were added/removed/renamed.

## Deprecation

- **Deprecate, don't delete.** Mark a rule superseded and point to its replacement
  so the reasoning survives.
- Record the trade-off in `.claude/debt-ledger.md` if the change leaves known debt.

## Maintenance cadence

- **[Weekly/per-PR]**: boy-scout fixes — obvious drift, stale paths.
- **[Monthly]**: work the debt ledger highest-priority first; run evals on
  iron-law and high-risk rules; prune rules no longer earning their token cost.
- **[Quarterly]**: re-check layer placement; retire dead features/plans.

## When agent and charter disagree

- The charter wins. If the charter is wrong, fix the charter — don't work around it.
- A rule that keeps getting violated isn't reaching that path: fix the rule (and
  add an eval), rather than repeating the correction.
